(Description)
- Given a signed 32-bit integer x, return x with its digits reversed. If reversing x causes the value to go outside the signed 32-bit integer range [-2^31, 2^31 - 1], then return 0.
- Assume the environment does not allow you to store 64-bit integers (signed or unsigned).

--- Solution ---
class Solution {
    public int reverse(int x) {
        int result = 0;

        while (x != 0) {
            int digit = x % 10;
            x /= 10;

            if (result > Integer.MAX_VALUE / 10
            || (result == Integer.MAX_VALUE && digit > 7)) {
                return 0;
            }

            if (result < Integer.MIN_VALUE / 10
            || (result == Integer.MIN_VALUE && digit < -8)) {
                return 0;
            }

            result = result * 10 + digit;
        } 

        return result;
    }
}

--- Approach ---
(Reverse Process): using the loop statement, convert the one digit by one digit from the given x to the integer, result.
(Checking over 32 digits): every adding last digit steps, it checks what would be the reversed value in terms of positive number as well as negative.
- It checks 
- 1. if the digit reach to the 32 bits digit, 
- 2. even though it reached, would the last added digit smaller than the 32 bits' one.
